lesson.title: Data Visualizations & EDA
lesson.summary: In this lesson, you will get hands on with creating plots in R.  This is where using R really shines, as you build amazing visualizations with only a few lines of code.

atoms.text:
# Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

In this lesson, you'll learn how to create data visualizations and explore data in R. This is just a glipse into a field called exploratory data analysis, commonly referred to as EDA. EDA is defined below.

"Exploratory data analysis (EDA) is a term for certain kinds of initial analysis and findings done with data sets, usually early on in an analytical process. Some experts describe it as “taking a peek” at the data to understand more about what it represents and how to apply it. Exploratory data analysis is often a precursor to other kinds of work with statistics and data." - [Techopedia](https://www.techopedia.com/definition/32962/exploratory-data-analysis-eda)

### What's Ahead

You will be applying your R skills to analyze data similar to Facebook data you might actually see if you worked at Facebook.  

The layout for this lesson will be that you:

1. Watch a video of how to approach a problem or build a visualization, where you are strongly encouraged to code along.

2. A notebook with solution code is provided following the video, as well as some additional nuggets of useful information.  This code is available in case you get stuck, as it is strongly recommended that you write the code yourself.

3. After working through all of the questions posted throughout the lesson, you are encouraged to explore your own questions.  

This lesson has a lot of information, but it is super useful in preparing you to complete the project.  It is exciting to start putting your skills to practice, and we can't wait to see what you will create!

### Before we begin...

Below is a video of Dean Eckles, a former Facebook Data Scientist, explaining the value of EDA.

atoms.text: # Notebooks vs. RStudio You probably noticed that the video environment in this lesson doesn't look like the environment you have been using in the classroom. We will be using Jupyter Notebooks + Graffiti to introduce new concepts for you to be able to run code directly in the browser. Unfortunately, the classroom does not have a built-in RStudio environment. However, you are welcome to run the code on your own machine using RStudio if you would prefer! Most industry and academic-related settings use RStudio. RStudio is the standard environment for working with R. Therefore, you will see RStudio used throughout the videos in this lesson, but you can follow along in the browser with Jupyter or run RStudio locally on your own machine.

atoms.title: Histogram of Users' Birthdays
atoms.instructor_notes:
**Note**: The use of the `scale_x_discrete()` layer as shown in the video is deprecated as of `ggplot2` version 2.0. You can use `scale_x_continuous()` instead to get the break points, or use `ggplot()` syntax as shown below. How to read Histograms and use them in R (note this post uses the base graphics package of R to create histograms; we'll be using the ggplot2 graphics package in this course)

Run the following code in R to get other themes. ``` install.packages('ggthemes', dependencies = TRUE) library(ggthemes) ```
The ggthemes package was developed by Jeffery Arnold. Check out examples of the themes on the github page.

Chris is using `theme_minimal()`with the font size set to 24, which is why his output might look slightly different than yours. You can set the same theme in R by running the following code, or you can set the theme to a choice of your own.
`theme_set(theme_minimal(24))`


Instead of using the `qplot()` function, you can also use the `ggplot()` function to create the histogram: ``` ggplot(aes(x = dob_day), data = pf) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:31) ``` For the most part, plots can be created using either qplot or ggplot. The reason for using one library vs. another is largely based on the personal experiences of the person writing the code. Some people are more comfortable with qplot syntax, while other people prefer ggplot syntax. However, in most circumstances, you can create the same plot in either library. For more information on this, you can visit the StackOverflow post here. When you register at a website, some sites have default settings that use the 1st day of the month under the birthday field. Some also use a default month of January. In the case of Facebook, Jan and the 1st are the first drop-down items that appear on the site. It's important to think about such details and the data generating process when exploring data.

atoms.title: Faceting
atoms.instructor_notes: **Note**: The use of the `scale_x_discrete()` layer as shown in the video is deprecated as of `ggplot2` version 2.0. You can use `scale_x_continuous()` instead, or use `ggplot()` syntax as shown below. It's best to create the plot in RStudio on your computer and examine at full screen. Faceting in ggplot2 Equivalent ggplot syntax: ``` ggplot(data = pf, aes(x = dob_day)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:31) + facet_wrap(~dob_month) ```

atoms.title: Moira's Outlier
atoms.instructor_notes: Bernstein, M. S., Bakshy, E., Burke, M., & Karrer, B. (2013). Quantifying the invisible audience in social networks. In Proceedings of the SIGCHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems (CHI 2013), pp. 21-30. Note that this study only asked people about posts with "Friends" privacy, not "Public" privacy settings

atoms.title: Friend Count
atoms.instructor_notes:
Create a histogram of friend_count using the `qplot()` syntax. We'll also accept the `ggplot()` syntax if you are familiar with it but additional parameters for setting the bin width or color won't be accepted. Keep it simple. You should create the histogram in R Studio on your computer first. Then, copy and paste your code into the {r} chunk. Remember to load the pseudo-facebook data set into a variable named `pf`. Otherwise, the grader will reject the answer.

Equivalent ggplot syntax for solution: ``` ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) + geom_histogram() ```

atoms.title: Limiting the Axes
atoms.instructor_notes:
Scales in ggplot2

Equivalent ggplot syntax: ``` ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) + geom_histogram() + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000)) ```

atoms.title: Exploring with Bin Width
atoms.instructor_notes: Bernstein, M. S., Bakshy, E., Burke, M., & Karrer, B. (2013). Quantifying the invisible audience in social networks. In Proceedings of the SIGCHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems (CHI 2013), pp. 21-30.

atoms.title: Adjusting the Bin Width
atoms.instructor_notes:
Scales in ggplot2
Original code: ``` qplot(x = friend_count, data = pf, binwidth = 25) + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000), breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) ``` Equivalent ggplot syntax: ``` ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 25) + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000), breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) ``` In the alternate solution below, the period or dot in the *formula* for `facet_grid()` represents all of the other variables in the data set. Essentially, this notation splits up the data by gender and produces three histograms, each having their own row. ``` qplot(x = friend_count, data = pf) + facet_grid(gender ~ .) ``` Equivalent ggplot syntax: ``` ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) + geom_histogram() + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000), breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) + facet_wrap(~gender) ```

atoms.title: Omitting NA Observations
atoms.instructor_notes:
NA Values

Why is the exclamation mark called bang?

Equivalent ggplot syntax: ``` ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) + geom_histogram() + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000), breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) + facet_wrap(~gender) ```

atoms.title: Tenure
atoms.instructor_notes: The parameter `color` determines the color **outline** of objects in a plot. The parameter `fill` determines the color of the **area** inside objects in a plot. You might notice how the color `black` and the hex code color of `#099DD9` (a shade of blue) are wrapped inside of `I()`. The `I()` functions stand for 'as is' and tells `qplot` to use them as colors. Learn more about what you can adjust in a plot by reading the ggplot theme documentation Equivalent ggplot syntax for plots: ``` ggplot(aes(x = tenure), data = pf) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 30, color = 'black', fill = '#099DD9') ggplot(aes(x = tenure/365), data = pf) + geom_histogram(binwidth = .25, color = 'black', fill = '#F79420') ```

atoms.title: Labeling Plots
atoms.instructor_notes:
Equivalent ggplot syntax:
```
ggplot(aes(x = tenure / 365), data = pf) +
  geom_histogram(color = 'black', fill = '#F79420') +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1, 7, 1), limits = c(0, 7)) +
  xlab('Number of years using Facebook') +
  ylab('Number of users in sample')
```

atoms.title: Box Plots
atoms.instructor_notes: How to read and use a Boxplot The interquartile range or IQR includes all of the values between the bottom and top of the boxes in the boxplot. Visualization of the IQR with a normal probability distribution function with \mu=1 and \sigma^2=1 (pdf). Intro to Descriptive Statistics Exercise: Match Box Plots

atoms.title: Box Plots, Quartiles, and Friendships
atoms.instructor_notes:
The question is **NOT** asking who initiated more friendships overall.

How to Interpret a Boxplot

The interquartile range or IQR includes all of the values between the bottom and top of the boxes in the boxplot.

There is an error on the screen in the answer video. The question should say **"Who made more friend requests on average - men or women?"**

atoms.title: Scatterplots
atoms.instructor_notes:
**Take notes and code along with Chris by working in this** Lesson 4 RMD file!

You can also read in the data using the following code: ``` read.delim('pseudo_facebook.tsv') ``` The equivalent ggplot syntax for the scatterplot: ``` ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count), data = pf) + geom_point() ``` There isn't a user interface (UI) feature on Facebook's website that causes people to pick the particular age of 69 or the older ages. In general, it is a good idea to think about what caused certain oddities or values in data sets. This can help explain dirty data.

atoms.title: Overlaying Summaries with Raw Data
atoms.instructor_notes: **Note**: ggplot 2.0.0 changes the syntax for parameter arguments to functions when using `stat = 'summary'`. To denote parameters that are being set on the function specified by `fun.y`, use the `fun.args` argument, e.g.: ``` ggplot( ... ) + geom_line(stat = 'summary', fun.y = quantile, fun.args = list(probs = .9), ... ) ``` To zoom in, the code should use the`coord_cartesian(xlim = c(13, 90))` layer rather than `xlim(13, 90)` layer. Look up documentation for `coord_cartesian()` and `quantile()` if you're unfamiliar with them. Try an example and practice problem for calculating quantiles (percentiles).

atoms.text:
### Recap

This final lesson had a lot of information to take in. It was designed to provide you with fundamental skills for being able to analyze data with R.

Specifically, you learned:

* How to use a library in R.  This lesson focused primarily on ggplot2.
* How to make plots for univariate data, including histograms and boxplots.
* How to make plots for univariate data, including scatter plots (with overlaying and accounting for overplotting).
* How to work with (psuedo) real, messy data with missing values, lots of points, and where everything doesn't work out perfectly.
* Common commands and statistical summary calculations in R.  Including using the `by` and `summary` commands.

For the project, you will have the opportunity to work with bikeshare data or data of your own choosing.  You will have the ability to ask the questions that YOU are most interested in, and answer those questions in the best way.  **Now that you have gone through an example with us in this lesson, you are ready to take the lead on an analysis of your own!**
